[{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><strong>Read each part carefully. Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</strong></p>\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a circular hoop that has a radius of R located on a horizontal surface. A small block is shown moving counterclockwise at a velocity of v around the inner perimeter of the hoop with one side of the block rubbing against the inner surface of the hoop.\" height=\"155\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252494.g01.png\" width=\"250\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"paragraph\">A small block of mass slides on a horizontal surface where friction between the block and the surface is negligible as it travels around the inside wall of a hoop of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r\"><math alttext=\"r\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The coefficient of friction between the block and the wall is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"mu sub k\"><math alttext=\"mu sub k\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The block is given an initial speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub 0\"><math alttext=\"v sub 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> tangent to the hoop and allowed to travel along the inside edge.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:a part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"a\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) The block is allowed to travel around the hoop for a time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. At that moment the speed of the block is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub 1\"><math alttext=\"v sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The experiment is repeated but the hoop is made larger so that the new radius is larger than in the first experiment. Will the speed of the block after a time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> be greater than, less than, or equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub 1\"><math alttext=\"v sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> ? Justify your answer.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"},{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:b part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"b\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) Students derive the following equation for the speed of the block as a function of time:<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span> <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1 over v of , t  equals  the fraction with numerator mu sub k , t , and denominator r, end fraction,   plus , 1 over  v sub 0  .\"><math alttext=\"1 over v of , t  equals  the fraction with numerator mu sub k , t , and denominator r, end fraction,   plus , 1 over  v sub 0  .\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Whether or not this equation is correct, does it match your claim in part (a)? Justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"},{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:c part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"c\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Briefly describe how students could use the equation from part (b) to derive an equation for the linear displacement of the block as a function of time.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"},{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:d part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"d\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Without deriving equations, describe what will happen to the net torque exerted on the block with respect to the center of the hoop as a function of time. Justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"},{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:e part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"e\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three line graphs in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane, labeled Graph A, Graph B, and Graph C. Each graph has a horizontal axis labeled t and a vertical axis labeled uppercase F sub lowercase f. In Graph A, the line begins on the vertical axis about halfway above the origin and curves gradually downwards and to the right, touching the horizontal axis at a point approximately two thirds of the way across the axis, after which it moves horizontally to the right and ends near the rightmost point along the axis. In Graph B, the line begins slightly less than halfway up the vertical axis above the origin, and it curves steeply upwards and to the right for a short distance until approximately one sixth of the way across the horizontal axis and three quarters of the way up the vertical axis. It then curves gradually upwards and to the right until it ends at the rightmost point along the horizontal axis and at the top of the vertical axis. In Graph C, the line begins slightly more than halfway up the vertical axis above the origin and curves downwards and to the right at an increasing rate. It ends near the rightmost point on the horizontal axis aligned with the origin.\" height=\"178\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252494.g02.png\" width=\"510\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) Students created the above graphs of the frictional force exerted on the block as a function of time. Which of the labeled graphs correctly models the frictional force exerted on the block as a function of time? Justify your answer.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"},{"id":"VR252494","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:f part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"f\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) Describe briefly the relationship between the magnitude of the gravitational force on the block and the force applied by the table upwards on the block. Justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252494_rubric"}]